 \section{Conclusion}
 \label{sec:conclusion}
 %% ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
 
-From the BDG integers $(1,-1,9,-16,8)$ and the sequential growth rule of Paper~I, the present paper develops the matter-and-force programme of Relational Actualism. Its strongest claims are structural: the five topology types, the renewal architecture, the confinement depths, and the organization of force mediation by discrete graph structure. On top of that structural core, the paper presents a number of numerical evaluations and phenomenological identifications, including candidate relations for couplings, masses, flavour parameters, and force ranges. Some of these are strikingly close to observed values, but they do not all stand at the same epistemic level, and should not be read as if they do.
-
-The paper therefore does not claim complete closure of the particle sector. Rather, it establishes a disciplined programme in which a substantial part of particle structure is constrained by discrete topology and renewal, while several quantitative bridges to observation remain to be sharpened, proved, or replaced. The particles are not, in this picture, excitations of fields on a background manifold. They are finite local topology classes---renewal motifs---that reproduce themselves under the BDG-filtered growth dynamics.
-
-\paragraph{Open targets.} The following are the most important unresolved items in this paper's programme: (i)~full derivation of the Higgs-sector mass relation from BDG dynamics; (ii)~closure of the $W$-mass conjecture; (iii)~first-principles derivation of $N_{\mathrm{eff}}$ in the proton mass cascade; (iv)~Haar-measure or algebraic derivation of the Cabibbo angle and CKM parameters; (v)~closure of the gauge-group identification at theorem level from BDG primitives to the continuum Standard-Model group; (vi)~first-principles derivation of the $\alpha_s(\mu)$ RG profile between the BDG UV and IR fixed points (which would close the $f_0$ bridge); (vii)~experimental discriminants separating RA predictions from Standard Model expectations; (viii)~an RA-native mechanism for the pion mass residual (see \S4.6), whether via a discrete Goldstone-like structure rooted in DAG directionality or via a structurally distinct RA-native mechanism with no Standard Model analog.
-
-Paper~III develops the macroscopic consequences: gravity, cosmology, and causal severance. Paper~IV develops the emergence of biological complexity from the same underlying percolation threshold.
+From the BDG integers $(1,-1,9,-16,8)$ and the sequential growth rule of Paper~I, the present paper develops the matter programme of Relational Actualism on a stricter native basis than earlier drafts. Its strongest present claims are structural: the finite motif census, finite closure lengths, ledger preservation, and orientation asymmetry in the stable $d=4$ regime. These are the pieces that now sit on the compiled native support chain.
+
+On top of that structural base, the paper advances a Nature-facing numerical programme for measured masses, radii, and interaction ranges. Some of those targets remain phenomenological or conjectural, and the paper now states that fact more sharply. Historical overlays involving running couplings, flavour mixing, gauge groups, or unification are no longer treated as active support; they are either archived comparison material or deferred native targets to be rebuilt directly from RA primitives.
+
+\paragraph{Open native targets.} The most important remaining targets are: (i) full closure of the proton mass cascade without auxiliary identifications; (ii) direct force-range and scattering predictions from the native motif census; (iii) a first-principles computation of the observed matter-sector excess from severance boundary data; (iv) direct decay and lifetime predictions for the finite motif families; and (v) sharper observational cartography from native motif classes to measured particle-sector regularities, without importing field-theoretic intermediates.
+
+Paper~III develops severance and the macroscopic observational programme. Paper~IV develops recursive organization, finite assembly depth, and the life / cognition frontier on the same discrete base.
 
